The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Merchant banking licence for Rabo arm

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Calcutta, June 7: Rabo India Securities, a 100 per cent subsidiary of Rabo India Finance, has received a category I merchant banking licence from the Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi).

 The merchant banker will kickstart its operations with an initial investment of Rs 5.5 crore and will offer an entire gamut of investment banking products, besides advising corporates on capital restructuring, maximisation of shareholders value and defence against takeovers. 

 This license also allows the company to execute open offers on behalf of its clients and participate in their capital raising programmes. 

 The Robo India subsidiary also aims to introduce a wide range of services covering tender offer management, acquisition support and public offering management. 

 It also has plans to extend its research support base to include services such as underwriting of securities (debt, equity and brokerage), mergers and acquisitions, initial public offerings and bond offerings. 

 Obtaining this license enhances our ability to provide a comprehensive customised range of products and services to the existing as well as prospective clients. Our expansion plans are well met with the addition of a merchant banking company. Leveraging our parent companys expertise and our local presence strike a harmonious balance for an even more substantial product suite, said Sanjiv Bhasin, managing director and chief executive officer of Rabo India Finance.

 Rabo India Finance has set admirable benchmarks for the Rabobank International franchise in Asia Pacific region and this latest development allows us to execute our strong vision towards a well-placed and increasingly competitive financial services franchise in India. Rabobanks global merchant banking expertise will add value to our demanding clients following the receipt of this licence, said Fergus Murphy, head of Asia Region, Rabobank International. 




